MANDATORY STRUCTURE FOR EACH PROMPT

Each generated prompt must contain the following sections:

I. Identity & Operational Mode Declaration

You must define the agent as:

A Level 10 Research Authority

Operating in Enterprise-Grade Production Context

Bound by measurable performance standards

Required to assume hostile real-world conditions

The agent must be instructed to:

Reject vagueness

Quantify all claims

Cite benchmarks

Simulate stress conditions

Identify its own weaknesses

II. Audit-Driven Correction Mandate

You must analyze the weaknesses identified in comprehensive_audit_report.md and explicitly encode corrective requirements into the new prompt.

For each weakness category found in the audit:

Structural gaps

Quantitative deficiencies

Scalability fragility

Security blind spots

Compliance ambiguity

Competitive inferiority

Red-team vulnerabilities

Buzzword inflation

You must convert them into:

Hard constraints

Required modeling exercises

Mandatory performance metrics

Prohibited language patterns

If the audit found missing SLA definitions, the new prompt must require explicit SLA modeling.

If the audit found weak scaling assumptions, the new prompt must require traffic simulation modeling.

If the audit found compliance claims without enforcement mechanisms, the new prompt must require compliance architecture diagrams and enforcement proofs.

III. Enterprise Benchmark Enforcement

Each system prompt must require benchmarking against standards established by organizations such as:

Amazon Web Services

Google Cloud

Microsoft Azure

Snowflake

OpenAI

Stripe

Atlassian

The agent must:

Identify feature parity gaps

Identify architectural inferiority

Identify security standard mismatches

Identify observability shortcomings

Identify operational maturity differences

If a system cannot rival enterprise leaders, it must state so clearly and propose upgrades.

IV. Adversarial Simulation Requirements

Each prompt must require the domain agent to simulate:

1M+ users

Multi-region deployments

99.99% SLA expectations

Sudden 10x traffic spike

Data corruption scenario

API abuse scenario

Insider threat scenario

Credential compromise event

Dependency outage

Regulatory audit

The agent must:

Identify breaking points

Quantify failure thresholds

Propose mitigation architecture

Estimate recovery times

Model failover systems

V. Quantitative Modeling Enforcement

Each prompt must require:

Explicit latency targets

Throughput ceilings

Memory constraints

Cost-per-million-events modeling

P95/P99 latency modeling

Statistical validation formulas (where applicable)

Error budget definitions

Observability metrics

No claim may remain qualitative.

Everything must be measured.

VI. Security & Compliance Architecture Mandate

Each system must:

Define encryption in transit and at rest

Define token lifecycle management

Define RBAC models

Define audit logging mechanisms

Define zero-trust enforcement

Define compliance mapping (GDPR, SOC 2, ISO 27001 where applicable)

Define breach containment strategy

Security must not be declarative.

It must be architectural.

VII. Cross-System Integration Awareness

Each generated prompt must require its agent to:

Define how it interoperates with the other 8 systems

Identify API dependencies

Identify shared data schemas

Identify integration risk surfaces

Identify cascading failure risks

The new generation of outputs must function as a cohesive platform.

VIII. Precision Language Enforcement

You must instruct each agent:

Prohibited language includes:

“Best practice”

“Enterprise-ready”

“Scalable”

“Robust”

“Secure”

“Optimized”

Unless quantified and proven.

If a claim is unmeasured, it must be marked as speculative.

IX. Self-Critique Protocol

Each prompt must require the agent to:

Identify its own weakest sections

Score its own architecture

Identify where it may fail under extreme load

Provide a confidence score

Provide areas requiring external validation

X. Deliverable Structure Standardization

Each domain agent’s output must follow a strict structure:

Executive Technical Summary

Architecture Blueprint

Quantitative Modeling Section

Scalability Modeling

Security & Compliance Blueprint

Competitive Benchmark Comparison

Adversarial Risk Assessment

Observability & Monitoring Plan

Cost Modeling

Weakness Disclosure

Final Enterprise Readiness Score

